Matrix Modification Example (Minesweeper-like Logic)
Overview
This C program creates a SIZE x SIZE matrix (grid) filled randomly with '0' and 'M' characters.

'M' represents a "mine".

'0' represents an empty cell.
After generating the original matrix, the program modifies it so that each non-mine cell contains the number of mines adjacent to it (similar to Minesweeper game rules).

How It Works
Matrix Creation

create_mat() allocates memory for a 2D array (char**) of size SIZE x SIZE.

Randomly fills the matrix with:

'M' with probability 1/5

'0' otherwise.

Randomness is seeded with time(NULL).

Printing the Matrix

print() outputs the current state of the matrix.

Modification Logic

modifate_matrix() loops over every cell in the matrix.

Calls check_and_change() for each cell.

check_and_change() Function

Checks the 8 neighboring cells around a given cell (i, j).

If a neighbor contains 'M', increments the value of the current cell (if it’s not a mine).

Increment is done on the ASCII code of '0', turning it into '1', '2', etc.

